         <note xml:id="misc_235" type="description">
            <term id="misc_235-term">Electricians</term>
            <gloss id="misc_235-gloss" target="#misc_235-term">
               <p>Davy uses it in the older meaning (incl. used by Franklin) to mean someone knowlegable about or who studies electricity.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_233" type="description">
            <term id="misc_233-term">torpedo</term>
            <gloss id="misc_233-gloss" target="#misc_233-term">
               <p>An electric ray fish.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_324" type="description">
            <term id="misc_324-term">The Réaumur scale</term>
            <gloss id="misc_324-gloss" target="#misc_324-term">
               <p>A temperature scale for which the melting and boiling points of water are defined as 0 and 80 degrees respectively.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_232" type="description">
            <term id="misc_232-term">gymnotus</term>
            <gloss id="misc_232-gloss" target="#misc_232-term">
               <p>Probably an electric eel, also known as the gynotus electricus or gymnotus electricus</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
